description: Authorities were notified and the cause of the accident is being investigated, the cruise line said.

description: The northeastern portion of the United States is ringing in the first weekend of spring with wet and wintry weather.

description: In his new book the journalist and CNN anchor writes a history of revolutionary changes, and how societies both embrace change, and resist it.

title: The Dish: New Orleans restaurants
description: We travel to the Crescent City, visiting three New Orleans restaurants, from a historic establishment in the Garden District to a restaurant that honors a family’s four generations. Watch these stories and more on "The Dish."

title: Spanish chef brings the tastes of Latin America to New York restaurants
description: Felipe Donnelly was born in Spain and spent his childhood traveling in South America and Mexico. Now, he has three restaurants in New York City, including the James Beard Award-nominated Colonia Verde.

title: Eye on America: Small business tries four-day work week
description: In Louisiana, we learn how a devastating drought has greatly diminished the area’s crawfish supply. Then in Ohio, we tour a small business that’s seeing promising results from a four-day work week model. Watch these stories and more on Eye on America with host Michelle Miller.

title: Former Nickelodeon Producer Dan Schneider responds to "Quiet on Set" accusations
description: In an interview posted to Dan Schneider's YouTube account this week, the producer addressed multiple accusations of inappropriate and abusive behavior made against him in the docuseries "Quiet on Set: The Dark Side of Kids TV."

title: Massive project works to restore Florida's Everglades
description: What's been called the largest restoration project in human history is underway in Florida's Everglades. Billions of dollars are being spent to restore millions of acres. Jeff Glor reports on the massive effort, which just years ago seemed like a pipe dream.

title: Saturday Sessions: Gary Clark Jr. performs "Maktub"
description: Acclaimed guitarist Gary Clark Jr. is making a return visit to Saturday Sessions to celebrate his new album, released on Friday. The Austin, Texas native is a four-time Grammy Award winner and captivating performer who has shared the stage with stars like Eric Clapton and Beyoncé. Now from "JPEG RAW," here is Gary Clark Jr. with "Maktub."

title: The Uplift: Nothing but net
description: Nets star Mikal Bridges fulfills his dream of teaching by working at a school in Brooklyn for the day. A doctor overcomes the odds to help other survivors of catastrophic injuries. Plus, behind the scenes of Drew Barrymore's talk show, and more heartwarming stories.

title: Swiping for love, but also for money — how dating apps can be a career
description: Single people are outsourcing their dating lives to companies — opening a new career path for others to judge, swipe and message romantic prospects.

title: Russia launches one-man, two-woman crew to space station
description: NASA astronaut Tracy Dyson, making her third flight, will spend six months aboard the station, replacing astronaut Loral O'Hara.

title: Mega Millions jackpot rises to $1.1 billion
description: No one has won the Mega Millions jackpot since Dec. 8, a string of 30 consecutive drawings without anyone taking home the top prize.

title: Meet the Michigan State Spartan using basketball to help his loved ones
description: Mady Sissoko didn't grow up with basketball. The Michigan State Spartans star, born in Mali, Africa, actually didn't play until he was a teen. Now 23, he's using the game to help himself, friends and family. Dana Jacobson shares his story.

title: Learn more about the unique, unusual sport of skijoring
description: Skijoring is a sport that's been around for over a century but remains a mystery to many. The sport combines a bit of the Old West with some newfangled ski tricks for a one-of-a-kind experience.

title: New museum exhibit excavates untold New York City stories
description: The Tenement Museum in Manhattan pays tribute to those often-invisible citizens of America: Immigrants and workers struggling through poverty to establish a home. But even here, someone was left out — until recently. Michelle Miller reports on the stories told at a new exhibit.

title: Eye Opener: Ukraine loses power under Russian barrage
description: More than a million people in Ukraine lost power after a sweeping Russian attack on the country’s electrical grid. Meanwhile, another U.N. vote for a cease-fire in Gaza failed. All that and all that matters in today’s Eye Opener.

title: Exclusive discounts from CBS Mornings Deals
description: On this edition of CBS Mornings Deals, Elizabeth Werner shows us items that might just become essentials in your everyday life. Visit cbsdeals.com to take advantage of these exclusive deals today. CBS earns commissions on purchases made through cbsdeals.com.

title: Idaho prison escapee and his accomplice arrested after 36 hours
description: The Idaho prison inmate and his accomplice who led police on a 36-hour manhunt are back behind bars. The white supremacist gang members are also suspected of killing two other men while on the run. Police also arrested a woman who they say was driving one of the cars the men were traveling in when they were recaptured.

title: World reacts to Princess Kate's cancer diagnosis
description: Catherine, the Princess of Wales, announced Friday that she has been diagnosed with cancer and was undergoing preventative chemotherapy. The announcement came after months of speculation about her health.

title: Eleven people arrested after deadly attack at concert hall in Russia
description: Russian authorities said that they have arrested 11 people, including four suspected gunmen, following the deadly attack at a concert hall near Moscow. Officials say at least 115 people were killed.

title: U.S. Senate averts partial government shutdown with late-night legislative package
description: The U.S. Senate passed an eleventh hour legislation package that thwarted a partial government shutdown. The $1.2 trillion package passed in a 74-24 vote.

title: Suspects arrested after Moscow concert hall attack leaves at least 115 dead
description: The Islamic State group has claimed responsibility for the attack in a statement posted on affiliated channels on social media.

title: What's in tattoo ink? Expert says some additives aren't on the packaging
description: Chemistry researchers found as much as 90% of tattoo inks in the U.S. might be mislabled, with some containing substances that could cause allergic reactions.

description: Lana Zak reports on Kate Middleton's cancer diagnosis, a deadly attack on a concert hall in Moscow, and a preview of the top NCAA Women's Basketball games.

title: How deep is the divide between U.S. and Israeli leaders?
description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is facing increased pressure from U.S. leaders as he vows to move forward with a ground invasion of Rafah. CBS News national security contributor Sam Vinograd joins with analysis.

title: Examining Princess Kate's cancer diagnosis
description: Catherine, Princess of Wales, revealed Friday that she was diagnosed with cancer. CBS News chief medical correspondent Dr. Jon LaPook takes a look at what her treatment could entail.

title: What led to Princess Kate's cancer announcement
description: After weeks of public speculation over her health and whereabouts, Kate Middleton, Princess of Wales, revealed in a video Friday she is being treated for cancer. CBS News royal contributor Amanda Foreman joins to discuss.

title: What to see during Broadway's packed spring season
description: A whopping 11 Broadway musicals are opening this spring, in addition to five star-studded plays. CBS News contributor Jamie Wax breaks it all down.

title: Coach Muffet McGraw talks women's March Madness
description: The highly-anticipated women's NCAA Tournament is finally underway. Basketball Hall of Fame Coach Muffet McGraw joins CBS News to discuss the star power oozing all over this year's bracket, and who she thinks is going all the way.

title: How Biden and Trump are reaching out to Latino voters
description: The Biden campaign is making a direct push for Latino support. CBS News political director Fin Gómez has the details.

title: House sends $1.2 trillion funding bill to Senate hours before deadline
description: The $1.2 trillion government funding bill has made its way to the Senate after the House passed it Friday morning. The upper chamber has until midnight Friday to send the bill to the president's desk to avert a partial shutdown. CBS News congressional correspondent Scott MacFarlane has the latest on where things stand.

title: What we know about Princess Kate's cancer diagnosis
description: Kate Middleton, the Princess of Wales, has been diagnosed with cancer and is undergoing chemotherapy. CBS News' Charlie D'Agata and Dr. Jon LaPook have more.

title: Texas man used photo of another passenger's boarding pass to get on flight, officials say
description: Newly obtained airport security video shows a suspected airplane stowaway taking a photo of another passenger's boarding pass in Salt Lake City, which authorities say he used to board a Southwest flight last weekend. Kris Van Cleave has details.

title: Princess Kate reveals cancer diagnosis. What is preventative chemotherapy?
description: Preventative chemotherapy​, which is usually referred to as "adjuvant chemotherapy," is an early treatment that is used to reduce the chances of cancer returning.

title: With deadline looming, Senate races to approve $1.2 trillion government spending package
description: Amid a divided Congress, the House Friday approved a $1.2 trillion government spending package, sending it to the Senate ahead of a midnight deadline in an effort to avoid a partial government shutdown. Scott MacFarlane has the latest.

title: New Jersey umpire hopes to make history as first woman ever to call MLB regular-season game
description: New Jersey native Jen Pawol has been umpiring spring training games over the past month in the Florida Grapefruit League. This season, she hopes to become the first woman ever to call a regular-season Major League Baseball game.
